        <section class="bg-gray-800 text-gray-100">
          <div class="container flex flex-col justify-center p-4 mx-auto md:p-8">
            <p class="block mb-2 text-base font-semibold uppercase lg:text-center text-teal-500">The Specifics</p>
            <h2 class="mb-12 text-4xl font-bold leadi lg:text-center sm:text-5xl font-header">Instructor Certification Requirements</h2>
            <div class="grid gap-10 md:gap-8 sm:p-3 md:grid-cols-2 lg:px-12 xl:px-32">
              <div class="col-span-2 md:col-span-1">
                <h3 class="font-semibold">Hold a commercial certificate and instrument rating</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-gray-400 font-sans">Obtaining your commercial certificate and instrument rating are prerequisites for qualifying to take your certified flight instructor certification practical exam.  By having these two requirements fulfilled, that also entails that you already have a valid medical certificate as well. A class one medical is needed for airline Part 121 operations while smaller Part 135 and Part 91 operations may only require a second class medical.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-span-2 md:col-span-1">
                <h3 class="font-semibold">Logged at least 250 hours total time</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-gray-400 font-sans">This requirement stems from having your commercial certificate done already.  You need to have adequate experience and knowledge prior to being awarded the privileges of teaching student pilots how to fly.  Of these 250 hours, at 15 hours must have been logged as PIC (pilot in command) in the category and class of aircraft that is appropriate to the flight instructor rating sought.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-span-2 md:col-span-1">
                <h3 class="font-semibold">Have an endorsement from an authorized instructor</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-gray-400 font-sans">You must receive an endorsement from an authorized instructor which is a product of training under an authorized instructor.  This endorsement must indicate that you are competent and possess instructional proficiency in stall awareness and spins.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-span-2 md:col-span-1">
                <h3 class="font-semibold">Pass knowledge test on aeronautical knowledge areas</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-gray-400 font-sans">In addition to understanding and having the aeronautical knowledge areas for being a pilot, you need to also know how to teach this knowledge to your future students.  This is known as the fundamentals of instructing which includes topics such as the learning process, elements of effective teaching, student evaluation and testing, course development, lesson planning, and classroom training techniques.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="text-slate-600 italic py-5 col-span-2">
                Reference Airman Practical Test Standards and 14 CFR ยง61.183 for the entire list of eligibility requirements.
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>
        </section>


